    "content": "<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n    <meta charset=\"UTF-8\" />\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1\" />\n    <title>NP-Completeness Demonstration</title>\n    <style>\n        body {\n            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\n            margin: 1em;\n            background: #f9f9f9;\n            color: #333;\n        }\n        h1, h2 {\n            color: #2c3e50;\n        }\n        section {\n            max-width: 900px;\n            margin: 0 auto 2rem auto;\n            background: white;\n            padding: 1.5em 2em;\n            border-radius: 8px;\n            box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);\n        }\n        .example {\n            margin-top: 1em;\n            padding: 1em;\n            background: #eef6fc;\n            border-left: 4px solid #3498db;\n            font-family: monospace;\n            white-space: pre-wrap;\n            overflow-x: auto;\n            max-height: 250px;\n        }\n        button {\n            margin: 0.5em 0 1em 0;\n            padding: 0.6em 1.2em;\n            font-size: 1em;\n            border: none;\n            border-radius: 4px;\n            background: #3498db;\n            color: white;\n            cursor: pointer;\n            transition: background-color 0.3s ease;\n        }\n        button:hover:not(:disabled) {\n            background: #2980b9;\n        }\n        button:disabled {\n            background: #a5c5e8;\n            cursor: default;\n        }\n        #output {\n            background: #f4f6f8;\n            border: 1px solid #ddd;\n            padding: 1em;\n            border-radius: 5px;\n            white-space: pre-wrap;\n            font-family: monospace;\n            max-height: 300px;\n            overflow-y: auto;\n        }\n        a {\n            color: #2980b9;\n        }\n        footer {\n            text-align: center;\n            font-size: 0.9em;\n            color: #666;\n            margin-top: 3rem;\n        }\n    </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n    <section>\n        <h1>Understanding NP-Completeness</h1>\n        <p>\n            In computer science, <strong>NP-Completeness</strong> is a concept in computational complexity theory. \n            It classifies problems based on their difficulty and how quickly they can be solved or verified by a computer.\n        </p>\n\n        <h2>Key Terms</h2>\n        <ul>\n            <li><strong>P:</strong> The set of problems that can be solved <em>quickly</em> (in polynomial time) by a deterministic computer.</li>\n            <li><strong>NP:</strong> The set of problems whose solutions can be <em>verified quickly</em> (in polynomial time), even if finding the solution might be hard.</li>\n            <li><strong>NP-Complete:</strong> Problems that are both in NP and as hard as any problem in NP. If you can solve any NP-Complete problem quickly, you can solve all NP problems quickly.</li>\n        </ul>\n\n        <h2>Why NP-Completeness Matters</h2>\n        <p>\n            NP-Complete problems represent some of the hardest problems in NP. Examples include:\n        </p>\n        <ul>\n            <li>Boolean satisfiability problem (SAT)</li>\n            <li>Subset sum problem</li>\n            <li>Travelling salesman problem (TSP)</li>\n            <li>3-coloring problem</li>\n        </ul>\n        <p>\n            No known algorithm solves NP-Complete problems quickly (in polynomial time). It is one of the greatest open questions in computer science whether P = NP or not.\n        </p>\n\n        <h2>Demonstration: The Subset Sum Problem</h2>\n        <p>\n            The <strong>Subset Sum Problem</strong>: Given a set of positive integers and a target sum, is there a subset of these numbers that adds up exactly to the target?\n        </p>\n        <p>This problem is NP-Complete.</p>\n\n        <button id=\"runBruteForce\">Run Brute Force Subset Sum (small set)</button> \n        <button id=\"runDP\" disabled>Run Pseudopolynomial DP Subset Sum (same set)</button>\n\n        <div id=\"output\" aria-live=\"polite\" aria-atomic=\"true\" style=\"margin-top:1em;\"></div>\n\n        <p><strong>Note:</strong> The brute force approach tries every possible subset (exponential time). The dynamic programming (DP) approach runs in pseudopolynomial time, which is efficient for small numbers but not polynomial in the input size (number of bits).</p>\n\n        <h3>Example Input Set:</h3>\n        <pre class=\"example\" id=\"inputSet\"></pre>\n\n        <h3>How the demonstration works:</h3>\n        <ul>\n            <li>Click \"Run Brute Force\" to compute if a subset sums to the target using simple enumeration.</li>\n            <li>After brute force completes, you can run the DP solution for comparison.</li>\n        </ul>\n\n        <p>\n            This highlights the complexity: brute force takes time exponential in the number of items (2^n), while DP can be more efficient but still not polynomial in the bit-length of input numbers.\n        </p>\n        <p>Learn more about NP-Completeness on the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NP-completeness\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Wikipedia page</a>.</p>\n    </section>\n\n    <script>\n        // Example input set and target sum\n        const numbers = [3, 34, 4, 12, 5, 2];\n        const target = 9;\n\n        const inputSetElem = document.getElementById(\"inputSet\");\n        inputSetElem.textContent = `Set: [${numbers.join(\", \")}]\\nTarget Sum: ${target}`;\n\n        const outputElem = document.getElementById(\"output\");\n        const btnBrute = document.getElementById(\"runBruteForce\");\n        const btnDP = document.getElementById(\"runDP\");\n\n        // Brute force subset sum (exponential time)\n        // Returns true if any subset sums to target\n        function bruteForceSubsetSum(arr, target) {\n            const n = arr.length;\n            let callCount = 0;\n            function helper(i, currentSum) {\n                callCount++;\n                if (currentSum === target) return true;\n                if (i === n || currentSum > target) return false;\n                // Include arr[i]\n                if (helper(i + 1, currentSum + arr[i])) return true;\n                // Exclude arr[i]\n                if (helper(i + 1, currentSum)) return true;\n                return false;\n            }\n            const result = helper(0, 0);\n            return {result, callCount};\n        }\n\n        // Dynamic Programming subset sum (pseudopolynomial time)\n        // Returns true if any subset sums to target\n        function dpSubsetSum(arr, target) {\n            const n = arr.length;\n            const dp = new Array(n + 1);\n            for (let i = 0; i <= n; i++) {\n                dp[i] = new Array(target + 1).fill(false);\n            }\n            for (let i = 0; i <= n; i++) dp[i][0] = true; // sum=0 is always possible\n\n            for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {\n                for (let sum = 1; sum <= target; sum++) {\n                    if (arr[i-1] > sum) {\n                        dp[i][sum] = dp[i-1][sum];\n                    } else {\n                        dp[i][sum] = dp[i-1][sum] || dp[i-1][sum - arr[i-1]];\n                    }\n                }\n            }\n            return dp[n][target];\n        }\n\n        // Format time in ms nicely\n        function formatTime(ms) {\n            if (ms < 1) return `${(ms * 1000).toFixed(2)} μs`;\n            if (ms < 1000) return `${ms.toFixed(2)} ms`;\n            return `${(ms / 1000).toFixed(2)} s`;\n        }\n\n        btnBrute.addEventListener(\"click\", () => {\n            outputElem.textContent = \"Running brute force subset sum...\\n(Warning: exponential time for large input sets)\";\n            btnBrute.disabled = true;\n            btnDP.disabled = true;\n            setTimeout(() => {\n                const start = performance.now();\n                const {result, callCount} = bruteForceSubsetSum(numbers, target);\n                const end = performance.now();\n\n                outputElem.textContent = \n`Brute Force Result: ${result ? \"Subset found ✅\" : \"No subset found ❌\"}\nTotal recursive calls: ${callCount}\nTime taken: ${formatTime(end - start)}\n\nYou can now run the dynamic programming approach for comparison by clicking the next button.`;\n                btnDP.disabled = false;\n            }, 50); // Give UI a moment to update\n        });\n\n        btnDP.addEventListener(\"click\", () => {\n            outputElem.textContent = \"Running dynamic programming subset sum...\";\n            btnDP.disabled = true;\n\n            setTimeout(() => {\n                const start = performance.now();\n                const result = dpSubsetSum(numbers, target);\n                const end = performance.now();\n\n                outputElem.textContent = \n`Dynamic Programming Result: ${result ? \"Subset found ✅\" : \"No subset found ❌\"}\nTime taken: ${formatTime(end - start)}\n\nThe DP algorithm runs in pseudopolynomial time, which is efficient for small targets but scales with the numbers' sizes.\n\nBoth approaches solve the problem, but the difference in their time complexities highlights challenges in solving NP-Complete problems efficiently.`;\n            }, 50);\n        });\n    </script>\n    <footer>\n        &copy; NP-Completeness Demo – For educational use\n    </footer>\n</body>\n</html>"
